    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Problem description.</p>\n<p>\nAtsi had his geometry classes today and he is too excited about it as he just thought of a new problem. He defined the beauty of an ordered sequence of points to be the sum of the areas of triangles formed by every adjacent points in the sequence with the origin. For example if the points (2, 0) and (0, 2) are adjacent then the area of the triangle with the origin is 1 unit(Area of an isoceles right angled triangle with side length 2).<br><br>Atsi gives you a sequence which is not ordered as of now. Can you help him order the sequence so as to maximize the beauty?\n</p>\n\n\n<h3>Input</h3>\n<p>Input description.</p>\n<p>The first line of the input contains an integer <b>T</b> denoting the number of test cases. The first line of each test case contains a single integer <b>N</b> denoting the number of points in the given sequence. Then follows <b>N</b> lines each containing two space separated integers <b>x<sub>i</sub></b> and <b>y<sub>i</sub></b> denoting the X and Y coordinates of the <b>ith</b> point.\n\n<h3>Output</h3>\n<p>Output description.</p>\n<p>For each test case, output a single integer denoting the maximum possible beauty of the given sequence when the given sequence is rearranged.</p>\n\n<h3>Constraints</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>T</b> \u2264 <b>5</b></li>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>N</b> \u2264 <b>15</b></li>\n<li><b>-10<sup>9</sup></b> \u2264 <b>x<sub>i</sub></b>, <b>y<sub>i</sub></b> \u2264 <b>10<sup>9</sup></b></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Subtasks</h3>\n<p>\n\t<b>Subtask 1(35 points):</b> <b>1</b> \u2264 <b>N</b> \u2264 <b>9</b><br>\n\t<b>Subtask 2(65 points):</b> Original constraints\n</p>\n\n<h3>Example</h3>\n<pre><b>Input:</b>\n3\n1\n0 1\n2\n0 1\n1 0\n3\n0 1\n1 1\n1 0\n\n<b>Output:</b>\n0.0\n0.5\n1.0\n</pre>\n<h3>Explanation</h3>\n<p><b>Example case 1.</b>There is one points so no triangle can be formed with the origin.<br>\n<b>Example case 2.</b>Only two possible ordering which does not change the answer.<br>\n<b>Example case 3.</b>The input in given order generates the maximum beauty.</p>",
